1st of all, thanks for your lesson, but I gotta say that the way people "make words shorter" in English is just ridiculous! And what I'd like to know is why??
These 10 abbreviations are just a single drop in the sea but they are so demonstrative! Why would you like to make shorter the word "barbecue", when it;s already nice and short word for itself? Why the hecky-ecky why? And all the ridiculousness of this¬†¬†reveals itself in the expressions from Latin. Look, she says:
"I used ee-jee to show these are examples, ok? So this means example.
This is different from ai-ee = aidot-eedot... wich is used to add clarity to something.."
She tries and says "ee-jee" first, but then she has to ¬†correct herself, adding eedot-jeedot" Well, isn't just saying "for example" would have been shorter"? Apparently not. These people love to confuse ourselves as well as others by making things more complicated! "for example" sounds much more clear than "eedot-jeedot!" And that is already pretty short! And it's clear! And it's nice. And it doesn't confuse the listener! And it doesn't make the speaker to repeat the same thought for ten times in a row! Use abbreviations as less ass possible, people! It makes any language sound better!

textDisplay:
+Mustafa Maden
The abbreviations are used as they are.PIN and ATM are noun phrases so can be treated as nouns. If you want to say, for example, 'The PIN's (the personal identification number's) last number is 7,' then that is fine. Also, if you want to say, 'The ATMs (automatic telling machines) are broken.' Then, that is fine too. But google will always say it's wrong :)

As for ASAP, it is an adverb. 'Please come as soon as possible/ Please come ASAP.'
RSVP is a verb. 'R√©pondez sil vous plais' is French for 'Please reply'. An example would be, 'RSVP ASAP' = 'Reply as soon as possible.'

In AmE you'll hear abbreviations used A LOT in speech. But in BrE they are used mostly for writing and you would not really hear them spoken.

textDisplay:
Thanh Hai Lam R.S.V.P. stands for a French phrase, "r√©pondez, s'il vous pla√Æt," which
means "please reply." The person sending the invitation wo¬≠uld like you
to tell him or her whether you accept or decline the invitation. That
is, will you be coming to the event or not? Etiquette
rules followed in most Western cultures require that if you receive a
formal, written invitation, you should reply promptly, perhaps that same
day. For hosts who are planning a dinner party, a wedding or a
reception, this is important from a practical point of view, because
they need to know how many people to count on and how much food
and drink to buy. More important, though, is the simple courtesy of
responding to someone who was nice enough to invite you, even if it is
to say that you regret that you will not be able to attend.
